The specific surface area and porous structure of pure MIL-101(Fe) and NQML-x were characterized by nitrogen adsorption–desorption isotherm. All the isotherms exhibit type IV isotherms in the IUPAC classification (
Fig. S2
), illustrating that they are typical mesoporous materials [45]. In addition, H4 hysteresis loops have been found in these isotherms within the range of P/P0 = 0.4 ∼ 0.9, which display horizontal and parallel adsorption and desorption branches, implying that there is a slit-like pore structure in the examined materials [46]. Additionally, the specific surface area, pore volume and pore diameter of these catalysts were conducted using BET and BJH methods, whose details are presented in Table 1 . The specific surface area, pore volume and pore diameter of MIL-101(Fe) are 593.32 cm2/g, 6.40 × 10-2 cm3/g and 18.53 nm, respectively. Nevertheless, the specific surface area of MIL-101(Fe) decreases after loading NCQDs, which may be because the loading of NCQDs blocked part of the pores in MIL-101(Fe) [47].

To further clarify the possible transformation pathways of pollutants during the process of TC photocatalytic degradation by NQML-8, gas chromatography mass spectrometer (GC–MS) was carried out to analyze the mass-to-charge ratio (m/z) and molecular structures of the intermediate products generated by TC (as depicted in 
                           Fig. S8
                        ). Based on the results, two possible transformation pathways during TC degradation are proposed (as seen in Fig. 9
                        ). Therein, eight intermediates (P11-P18) can be detected in Path 1, P11 (m/z = 415) is acquired by the deamination and dehydration in TC, and this intermediate can be further demethylated to form P12 (m/z = 401). Under the attack of active species, the ring-opening reaction of P12 occurs to form P13 (m/z = 306), P14 (m/z = 274) and P15 (m/z = 181). Subsequently, P13, P14 and P15 are scissored into the fragments with small molecular P16, P17 (m/z = 183, 147), which can be further decomposed to P18 (m/z = 114) under the constantly oxidation by active species. In another aspect, the double bonds, phenolic hydroxyl groups and amine groups in TC molecules are liable to the assault of active species because of the crowded electron density of TC. Under this circumstances, the double bond of the third carbocyclic ring connected to the hydroxyl group is preferentially attacked by active species to generate P21 (m/z = 461) (Path 2). Afterwards, the ring cleavage takes place in P21 to obtain P22 (m/z = 297). In addition, P24 (m/z = 156) is considered to be the product of P22 through deamination and multi-step ring-opening processes, thus further generating P25 (m/z = 114) via the oxidation process. Finally, the terminal intermediate products can be further oxidized into CO2 and H2O.
